<div id="unit7" class="unit-header">
  <div class="unit-num">Unit 7</div>
  <h2>Reading and Interpretation of Financial Statements</h2>
</div>

<div class="warn-box"><strong>Key Techniques to Remember:</strong> Comparative Statements → Common-Size Statements → Trend Analysis → Ratio Analysis</div>

<div class="section-band"><span class="mark-pill m5">5 Marks</span><hr></div>

<div class="qa-card">
  <div class="qa-q"><div class="qnum">1</div>What is an Annual Report? List its main components.</div>
  <div class="qa-a">
    An <span class="key-term">Annual Report</span> is a document prepared by every company as a regulatory requirement providing information on financial results, operations, and conditions over the previous accounting year.<br><br>
    <strong>Main Components:</strong>
    <ul class="list">
      <li>General information about operations and business segments</li>
      <li>Director's Report + Audited Financial Statements (P&L, Balance Sheet, Cash Flow)</li>
      <li>Management Discussion and Analysis (MDA) – future strategy & composite performance summary</li>
      <li>Corporate Governance Report</li>
      <li>Board of Directors, management committee, statutory auditor listing</li>
      <li>Shareholding pattern</li>
      <li>Share price data and dividend declared</li>
    </ul>
    <strong>Other Disclosures (classified as):</strong>
    <table>
      <tr><th>Companies Act</th><th>Accounting Standards</th><th>Listing Agreement</th><th>Voluntary</th></tr>
      <tr><td>Director's Report, Auditor's Report</td><td>Contingent Liabilities, Related Party Disclosures</td><td>Corporate Governance, Segment Reporting</td><td>Value Added Statement, Brand Valuation, HR Accounting</td></tr>
    </table>
  </div>
</div>

<div class="qa-card">
  <div class="qa-q"><div class="qnum">2</div>Who are the users of financial statements? State their information needs.</div>
  <div class="qa-a">
    <strong>A. Internal Users:</strong>
    <table>
      <tr><th>User</th><th>Information Needed</th></tr>
      <tr><td>Owners/Shareholders</td><td>Profit level, EPS, Dividend per Share, share value appreciation</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Management</td><td>All financial data for rational decisions – pricing, future policies</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Employees</td><td>Profitability (to validate bonus), job security</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Trade Unions</td><td>Growth trends for wage negotiations</td></tr>
    </table>
    <strong>B. External Users:</strong>
    <table>
      <tr><th>User</th><th>Information Needed</th></tr>
      <tr><td>Prospective Investors</td><td>Earning capacity, liquidity, solvency, safety of investment</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Lenders/Banks</td><td>Ability to pay interest and repay principal</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Trade Creditors</td><td>Creditworthiness and financial soundness</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Government</td><td>Tax collection, national income data, law compliance</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Researchers</td><td>Business affairs, industry practices</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Stock Exchanges</td><td>Fair share price determination</td></tr>
    </table>
  </div>
</div>

<div class="qa-card">
  <div class="qa-q"><div class="qnum">3</div>What is the Information Gap in Financial Statements?</div>
  <div class="qa-a">
    <span class="key-term">Information Gap</span> = Deviation between what users <em>expect</em> from financial statements and what is <em>actually provided</em>.<br><br>
    <strong>Causes / Limitations:</strong>
    <ul class="list">
      <li><strong>Historical Cost Basis:</strong> Statements show past costs, not current market values. Assets like fixed assets are not adjusted to current worth.</li>
      <li><strong>Personal Judgment:</strong> Depreciation method, amortization, asset valuation depends on accountant's personal discretion.</li>
      <li><strong>Accounting Policies:</strong> Going concern concept means assets are not valued at realizable/replacement value.</li>
      <li><strong>Window Dressing:</strong> Firms may manipulate figures to present a rosier picture.</li>
      <li><strong>Inflation Impact:</strong> Data becomes incomparable over time due to price level changes.</li>
    </ul>
  </div>
</div>

<div class="qa-card">
  <div class="qa-q"><div class="qnum">4</div>What is Comparative Statement Analysis? State its purpose and limitations.</div>
  <div class="qa-a">
    <span class="key-term">Comparative Statements</span> display financial data from two or more years side by side to show absolute and percentage changes.<br><br>
    <strong>Format – 5 columns:</strong> Item | Year 1 (₹) | Year 2 (₹) | Increase/Decrease (₹) | % Change<br><br>
    <strong>Purpose:</strong>
    <ul class="list">
      <li>Measure effects of business operations over time</li>
      <li>Show trends in costs, revenues, profits</li>
      <li>Identify strong and weak areas</li>
      <li>Compare performance with industry average</li>
      <li>Assist in forecasting future profitability</li>
    </ul>
    <strong>Limitations:</strong>
    <ul class="list">
      <li>Does not show relative weight of components (e.g., expense as % of sales)</li>
      <li>Not useful for comparing two different companies (no common base)</li>
    </ul>
  </div>
</div>

<div class="qa-card">
  <div class="qa-q"><div class="qnum">5</div>What is Trend Analysis? How are Trend Percentages calculated?</div>
  <div class="qa-a">
    <span class="key-term">Trend Analysis</span> involves calculating the percentage change of financial data over multiple years taking a <strong>base year as 100%</strong>. It shows the direction (upward/downward trend) of financial variables.<br><br>
    <div class="formula">Trend % = (Value in Current Year / Value in Base Year) × 100</div>
    <strong>Example:</strong> Machinery in Base Year 2019 = ₹4,00,000. In 2022 = ₹5,00,000<br>
    Trend % = (5,00,000 / 4,00,000) × 100 = <strong>125%</strong> (25% growth)<br><br>
    <strong>Care before Trend Analysis:</strong>
    <ul class="list">
      <li>Use consistent accounting policies across years</li>
      <li>Choose a <em>normal and representative year</em> as base year</li>
      <li>Adjust for price level changes (inflation)</li>
      <li>Only compare logically related items</li>
    </ul>
  </div>
</div>

<div class="section-band"><span class="mark-pill m10">10 Marks</span><hr></div>

<div class="qa-card">
  <div class="qa-q"><div class="qnum">1</div>Explain all major Techniques of Financial Statement Analysis.</div>
  <div class="qa-a">
    Financial Statement Analysis = Systematic numerical calculation of relationships between figures to measure profitability, operational efficiency, and growth.<br><br>
    <strong>Four Major Techniques:</strong><br><br>
    <strong>1. Comparative Statements</strong>
    <ul class="list">
      <li>Side-by-side comparison of two or more years</li>
      <li>Shows absolute (₹) and percentage (%) change</li>
      <li>Types: Comparative P&L and Comparative Balance Sheet</li>
    </ul>
    <strong>2. Common-Size Statements (Vertical Analysis)</strong>
    <ul class="list">
      <li>All items expressed as % of a base figure (Sales for P&L; Total Assets for B/S)</li>
      <li>Useful for comparing companies of different sizes</li>
      <li>Enables inter-firm comparison on equal footing</li>
    </ul>
    <strong>3. Trend Analysis</strong>
    <ul class="list">
      <li>Base year = 100%; all other years calculated as % of base</li>
      <li>Shows direction of change (growth or decline) over multiple years</li>
      <li>Formula: Trend % = (Current Year Value / Base Year Value) × 100</li>
    </ul>
    <strong>4. Ratio Analysis</strong>
    <ul class="list">
      <li>Mathematical relationship between two financial figures</li>
      <li>Expressed as: Pure Ratio (2:1), Rate (5 times), or Percentage (20%)</li>
      <li>Categories: Liquidity, Solvency, Activity, Profitability, Market Test</li>
    </ul>
    <div class="tip-box"><strong>Ratio expressed in 3 ways:</strong><br>
    A) Pure Ratio: Current Assets ₹2,00,000 / CL ₹1,00,000 = 2:1<br>
    B) Rate/Times: Credit Sales ₹2,00,000 / Debtors ₹40,000 = 5 times<br>
    C) Percentage: Profit ₹2,000 / Capital ₹10,000 × 100 = 20%</div>
  </div>
</div>

<div class="section-band"><span class="mark-pill m20">20 Marks</span><hr></div>

<div class="qa-card">
  <div class="qa-q"><div class="qnum">1</div>Explain the structure of P&L Account and how to analyse it. Also explain Balance Sheet analysis and Cash Flow analysis with their importance.</div>
  <div class="qa-a">
    <strong>I. Structure and Analysis of Profit &amp; Loss Account:</strong><br>
    The P&L account (Income Statement) shows profit/loss for a period by comparing total revenues vs total costs.<br><br>
    <strong>Key Components of P&L:</strong>
    <table>
      <tr><th>Component</th><th>Meaning</th></tr>
      <tr><td>Net Sales (Revenue)</td><td>Value of goods/services sold (net of returns, discounts)</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Cost of Goods Sold (COGS)</td><td>Direct material + labour + overhead costs</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Gross Profit</td><td>Net Sales − COGS</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Operating Expenses</td><td>Selling expenses + Administrative expenses</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Operating Income</td><td>Gross Profit − Operating Expenses</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Income Before Tax</td><td>Operating Income ± non-operating items</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Net Income</td><td>After deducting all expenses, taxes, depreciation</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Earnings Per Share (EPS)</td><td>Net Profit / No. of outstanding shares</td></tr>
    </table>
    <strong>How to Analyse P&L (Comparative Example):</strong><br>
    Bharat Trading Co. – Sales increased 20% but COGS increased 33.33% → Gross Profit fell 11.11%. This indicates <em>production inefficiency</em>. Admin expenses rose 32% → serious concern. But selling expenses fell 8% and dividend income rose 200% → overall net profit rose 25.97%.<br><br>
    <strong>II. Balance Sheet Analysis:</strong><br>
    Balance Sheet = Statement of financial position on a specific date. Analysed using:<br>
    <ul class="list">
      <li><em>Financial Strength Ratios:</em> Working Capital (CA−CL), Debt-to-Equity</li>
      <li><em>Activity Ratios:</em> Debtor collection, Inventory management</li>
      <li><em>Comparative Balance Sheet:</em> Shows % change in each item over years</li>
    </ul>
    <strong>Example from Varsha International Engineering Ltd.:</strong><br>
    Fixed Assets increased 50%, Current Assets increased 80%, Working Capital increased 66.67%, but Reserves decreased 33.33% → The company is expanding aggressively (more loans taken – 60% increase in 12% loan) while reserves fell. Risky expansion strategy.<br><br>
    <strong>III. Cash Flow Statement Analysis:</strong><br>
    Why Cash Flow Statement is needed:
    <ul class="list">
      <li>Demonstrates financial strength (actual cash position)</li>
      <li>Shows changes in assets, liabilities, equity in cash terms</li>
      <li>Enables forecasting of future cash flows</li>
      <li>Required for applying for loans or issuing bonds</li>
    </ul>
    Three sections: Operating Activities → Investing Activities → Financing Activities<br><br>
    <strong>IV. Importance of Analysis and Interpretation:</strong>
    <ul class="list">
      <li>Decisions based on logical, scientific analysis (not intuition)</li>
      <li>Helps understand complex business relationships</li>
      <li>Scientifically-based findings are comparable across firms</li>
      <li>Verifies/examines intuition-based conclusions</li>
      <li>Assists in inter-firm (between companies) and intra-firm (within company) comparison</li>
    </ul>
  </div>
</div>

