<div id="unit8" class="unit-header" style="border-left-color: var(--accent2);">
  <div class="unit-num" style="color:var(--accent2)">Unit 8</div>
  <h2>Introduction to Financial Management</h2>
</div>

<div class="section-band"><span class="mark-pill m5">5 Marks</span><hr></div>

<div class="qa-card">
  <div class="qa-q"><div class="qnum">1</div>Define Financial Management. What are its key decisions?</div>
  <div class="qa-a">
    <span class="key-term">Financial Management</span> means planning, organizing, directing and controlling the financial activities such as procurement and utilization of funds of the enterprise.<br><br>
    <strong>Three Key Financial Decisions:</strong>
    <table>
      <tr><th>Decision</th><th>Nature</th><th>Examples</th></tr>
      <tr><td><strong>Investment Decision</strong></td><td>Where to invest funds?</td><td>Capital budgeting (fixed assets), Working capital decisions</td></tr>
      <tr><td><strong>Financing Decision</strong></td><td>How to raise funds?</td><td>Type of source (equity/debt), period, cost, returns</td></tr>
      <tr><td><strong>Dividend Decision</strong></td><td>How to distribute profits?</td><td>Dividend rate for shareholders vs. Retained earnings for expansion</td></tr>
    </table>
    A 4th decision is <strong>Liquidity Decision</strong> – managing current assets to maintain sufficient liquidity.
  </div>
</div>

<div class="qa-card">
  <div class="qa-q"><div class="qnum">2</div>Explain the three phases in the Evolution of Financial Management.</div>
  <div class="qa-a">
    <table>
      <tr><th>Phase</th><th>Focus</th><th>Features</th></tr>
      <tr><td><strong>Traditional Phase</strong></td><td>Episodic events needing funds (mergers, expansions)</td><td>Heavy legal/procedural emphasis; Outsiders' perspective (investment bankers, regulators)</td></tr>
      <tr><td><strong>Transitional Phase</strong></td><td>Problems in fund analysis, planning and control</td><td>Same nature as traditional but more internal focus on financial problems</td></tr>
      <tr><td><strong>Modern Phase</strong></td><td>Rational matching of funds to uses</td><td>Application of economic theories + quantitative methods; financial modelling, demand forecasting, risk analysis; mathematics & statistics applied</td></tr>
    </table>
    <div class="tip-box">Modern phase is characterized by: macro-economic focus, quantitative tools, and rational decision criteria for fund allocation.</div>
  </div>
</div>

<div class="qa-card">
  <div class="qa-q"><div class="qnum">3</div>Compare Profit Maximisation vs Wealth Maximisation as objectives of Financial Management.</div>
  <div class="qa-a">
    <table>
      <tr><th>Basis</th><th>Profit Maximisation</th><th>Wealth Maximisation</th></tr>
      <tr><td>Goal</td><td>Increase accounting profit</td><td>Increase market value of shares / shareholders' wealth</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Time Horizon</td><td>Short-term</td><td>Long-term</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Risk</td><td>Ignores risk</td><td>Considers risk and uncertainty</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Time Value</td><td>Ignores time value of money</td><td>Recognizes time value (discounting)</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Measure</td><td>Accounting profits (vague)</td><td>Cash flows (objective)</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Market Focus</td><td>Internal/operational efficiency</td><td>Market share, long-term growth, leadership position</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Advocates</td><td>Traditional accounting view</td><td>Ezra Solomon (Stanford), Prof. Irwin Friend</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Also known as</td><td>—</td><td>Value Maximisation / NPV Maximisation</td></tr>
    </table>
    <div class="warn-box"><strong>Conclusion:</strong> Wealth Maximisation is the BETTER objective because it considers risk, time value of money, and long-term sustainability. Profit maximisation is vague, ignores risk, and can encourage monopolistic tendencies.</div>
  </div>
</div>

<div class="qa-card">
  <div class="qa-q"><div class="qnum">4</div>What is Agency Relationship? What are its problems and costs?</div>
  <div class="qa-a">
    <span class="key-term">Agency Relationship:</span> When owners (principals) delegate decision-making power to managers (agents). In a joint stock company, there is an agency relationship between shareholders (principals) and managers (agents).<br><br>
    <strong>Problems of Agency Relationship:</strong>
    <ul class="list">
      <li>Agents may act in <em>self-interest</em> rather than the principal's interest</li>
      <li>Financial misappropriation (e.g., Enron, Xerox frauds)</li>
      <li>Misuse of company funds for personal benefits (fringe benefits)</li>
      <li>Managers chasing short-term results (overstocking, huge discounts) to hit targets at the cost of long-term health</li>
      <li>Lack of effort in expanding market for new business</li>
    </ul>
    <strong>Costs of Agency Relationship:</strong>
    <ul class="list">
      <li><em>Monitoring costs:</em> Costs incurred by principals to monitor agents (audits, reports)</li>
      <li><em>Bonding costs:</em> Costs incurred by agents to signal their trustworthiness</li>
      <li><em>Residual loss:</em> Value lost due to divergence between agent decisions and optimal decisions</li>
    </ul>
  </div>
</div>

<div class="qa-card">
  <div class="qa-q"><div class="qnum">5</div>Distinguish Economic Profit from Accounting Profit.</div>
  <div class="qa-a">
    <div class="formula">Accounting Profit = Total Revenue − Explicit Costs<br>
Economic Profit  = Total Revenue − (Explicit Costs + Implicit Costs)</div>
    <table>
      <tr><th>Basis</th><th>Accounting Profit</th><th>Economic Profit</th></tr>
      <tr><td>Definition</td><td>Net earnings as per Income Statement</td><td>Value of free cash flow generated above ALL costs</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Costs Considered</td><td>Explicit costs only (wages, rent, materials)</td><td>Explicit + Implicit costs (opportunity costs)</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Measure</td><td>Net income (accounting basis)</td><td>Free cash flow (actual cash generated)</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Implicit Costs</td><td>Not considered</td><td>Included (opportunity cost of capital, using own assets)</td></tr>
    </table>
    <div class="tip-box"><strong>Implicit Cost Example:</strong> A firm uses its own building instead of renting it out. The forgone rental income is an implicit cost that reduces economic profit but does not appear in accounting profit.</div>
  </div>
</div>

<div class="section-band"><span class="mark-pill m20">20 Marks</span><hr></div>

<div class="qa-card">
  <div class="qa-q"><div class="qnum">1</div>Discuss the Role, Significance, and Objectives of Financial Management. Explain the organisation structure of the Finance function.</div>
  <div class="qa-a">
    <strong>I. Significance of Financial Management:</strong>
    <ul class="list">
      <li>Ensures adequate and regular supply of funds for operations</li>
      <li>Helps in optimal utilisation of funds (profitability, liquidity, safety)</li>
      <li>Minimises cost of capital through sound capital structure</li>
      <li>Maintains good relations with investors, employees, customers</li>
      <li>Coordinates finance department with other departments</li>
      <li>Facilitates financial planning, control and decision-making</li>
    </ul>
    <strong>II. Principles of Financial Management (Four Key Decisions):</strong>
    <div class="concept-grid">
      <div class="concept-box">
        <h4>Investment Decision</h4>
        <p>Capital Budgeting (fixed assets) + Working Capital Decisions. Where to deploy company funds?</p>
      </div>
      <div class="concept-box">
        <h4>Financing Decision</h4>
        <p>Raise funds from equity, debt, or a mix. Consider cost, risk, period, and returns.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="concept-box">
        <h4>Dividend Decision</h4>
        <p>Distribute net profit as dividends vs. retain for growth. Determines dividend rate.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="concept-box">
        <h4>Liquidity Decision</h4>
        <p>Manage current assets to maintain enough cash for day-to-day operations.</p>
      </div>
    </div>
    <strong>III. Objectives of Financial Management:</strong>
    <ul class="list">
      <li>Ensure adequate and regular supply of funds</li>
      <li>Provide fair rate of return to capital suppliers</li>
      <li>Efficient utilisation of capital (profitability + liquidity + safety)</li>
      <li>Minimise cost of capital (optimal capital structure)</li>
      <li>Co-ordinate finance with other departments</li>
      <li>Ultimately: <strong>Wealth Maximisation</strong> (market value of shareholders' wealth)</li>
