<div id="unit9" class="unit-header" style="border-left-color: var(--accent3);">
  <div class="unit-num" style="color:var(--accent3)">Unit 9</div>
  <h2>Time Value of Money</h2>
</div>

<div class="warn-box"><strong>Core Concept:</strong> ₹100 today &gt; ₹100 in the future — because money can be invested to earn returns. This is the Time Value of Money (TVM).</div>

<div class="section-band"><span class="mark-pill m5">5 Marks</span><hr></div>

<div class="qa-card">
  <div class="qa-q"><div class="qnum">1</div>What is Time Value of Money? Why does money have time value?</div>
  <div class="qa-a">
    <span class="key-term">Time Value of Money (TVM):</span> A sum of money is worth <strong>more today</strong> than the same sum in the future because of its earning potential (interest, investments).<br><br>
    <strong>Reasons for Time Value:</strong>
    <ul class="list">
      <li>General preference for <em>current consumption</em> over future consumption</li>
      <li>Capital can generate <em>positive returns</em> when invested</li>
      <li>Inflation reduces purchasing power of money over time</li>
      <li>Future cash flows are <em>uncertain</em> (risk)</li>
    </ul>
    <strong>Two Key Processes:</strong>
    <ul class="list">
      <li><em>Compounding:</em> Converting present value → future value (growing money forward)</li>
      <li><em>Discounting:</em> Converting future value → present value (bringing money back)</li>
    </ul>
  </div>
</div>

<div class="qa-card">
  <div class="qa-q"><div class="qnum">2</div>State the Future Value formula and calculate: ₹1,000 at 10% for 3 years.</div>
  <div class="qa-a">
    <div class="formula">FV = PV × (1 + k)ⁿ<br>Where: FV = Future Value | PV = Present Value | k = Interest Rate | n = Number of years</div>
    <strong>Example: ₹1,000 at 10% for 3 years</strong>
    <table>
      <tr><th>Year</th><th>Opening Principal</th><th>Interest (10%)</th><th>Closing Amount</th></tr>
      <tr><td>1</td><td>₹1,000</td><td>₹100</td><td>₹1,100</td></tr>
      <tr><td>2</td><td>₹1,100</td><td>₹110</td><td>₹1,210</td></tr>
      <tr><td>3</td><td>₹1,210</td><td>₹121</td><td>₹1,331</td></tr>
    </table>
    <div class="formula">FV = 1,000 × (1.10)³ = 1,000 × 1.331 = ₹1,331</div>
  </div>
</div>

<div class="qa-card">
  <div class="qa-q"><div class="qnum">3</div>Explain the Rule of 72 and Rule of 69 (Doubling Period).</div>
  <div class="qa-a">
    <strong>Doubling Period</strong> = Time required to double an investment at a given interest rate.<br><br>
    <strong>Rule of 72 (Approximate):</strong>
    <div class="formula">Doubling Period ≈ 72 / Interest Rate</div>
    Example: At 8% interest → 72/8 = <strong>9 years</strong> to double<br><br>
    <strong>Rule of 69 (More Accurate):</strong>
    <div class="formula">Doubling Period = 0.35 + (69 / Interest Rate)</div>
    Example: At 10% interest → 0.35 + (69/10) = 0.35 + 6.9 = <strong>7.25 years</strong><br><br>
    <strong>Quick Reference Table:</strong>
    <table>
      <tr><th>Interest Rate</th><th>3%</th><th>5%</th><th>8%</th><th>10%</th><th>12%</th></tr>
      <tr><td>Doubling Period</td><td>~23 yrs</td><td>~14 yrs</td><td>~9 yrs</td><td>~7 yrs</td><td>~6 yrs</td></tr>
    </table>
  </div>
</div>

<div class="qa-card">
  <div class="qa-q"><div class="qnum">4</div>What is an Annuity? Distinguish Regular Annuity from Annuity Due.</div>
  <div class="qa-a">
    <span class="key-term">Annuity</span> = A stream of <strong>uniform periodic cash flows</strong> over a defined period.<br>
    Examples: Life insurance premium, recurring bank deposits, loan EMIs.<br><br>
    <table>
      <tr><th>Feature</th><th>Regular Annuity (Deferred)</th><th>Annuity Due</th></tr>
      <tr><td>Cash Flow Timing</td><td>At the <em>END</em> of each period</td><td>At the <em>BEGINNING</em> of each period</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Future Value</td><td>Lower (last payment earns no interest)</td><td>Higher (each payment earns 1 extra period of interest)</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Example</td><td>₹10,000/year for 5 yrs @10% → FV = ₹61,051</td><td>₹10,000/year for 5 yrs @10% → FV = ₹67,156</td></tr>
    </table>
    <div class="formula">FV of Regular Annuity = A × [(1+k)ⁿ − 1] / k<br>
FV of Annuity Due = A × [(1+k)ⁿ − 1] / k × (1+k)</div>
  </div>
</div>

<div class="qa-card">
  <div class="qa-q"><div class="qnum">5</div>What is Present Value (Discounting)? Give the formula and an example.</div>
  <div class="qa-a">
    <span class="key-term">Present Value (PV)</span> is the current worth of a future sum of money, discounted at a given rate of return.<br>
    Discounting is the <em>reverse of compounding</em>.<br><br>
    <div class="formula">PV = FV / (1 + k)ⁿ   OR   PV = FV × PVIF(k,n)
    
PV of Uneven Cash Flows = A₁/(1+k)¹ + A₂/(1+k)² + ... + Aₙ/(1+k)ⁿ</div>
    <strong>Example:</strong> What is the PV of ₹1,331 receivable after 3 years at 10% discount rate?<br>
    PV = 1,331 / (1.10)³ = 1,331 / 1.331 = <strong>₹1,000</strong><br><br>
    <div class="tip-box"><strong>Key Facts:</strong><br>
    • PVIF = 1/FVIF (they are reciprocals of each other)<br>
    • If discount rate increases → PV decreases (inverse relationship)<br>
    • PV interest factor for money on hand today = 1.0</div>
  </div>
</div>

<div class="section-band"><span class="mark-pill m20">20 Marks</span><hr></div>

<div class="qa-card">
  <div class="qa-q"><div class="qnum">1</div>Explain Time Value of Money in detail – Compounding, Discounting, Annuities, and their applications in financial decisions.</div>
  <div class="qa-a">
    <strong>I. Time Value of Money – Concept &amp; Reasons</strong><br>
    TVM = Money today is worth more than the same amount in the future due to its earning potential.<br>
    Reasons: Current preference, positive returns from investment, inflation, uncertainty.<br><br>
    <strong>II. Future Value – Compounding</strong>
    <div class="formula">FV = PV × (1 + k)ⁿ  [Annual Compounding]
FV = PV × (1 + k/m)^(mn)  [Shorter Period Compounding]
FV = PV × e^(kn)  [Continuous Compounding, e = 2.71828]</div>
    <strong>Compounding Frequency Comparison (₹5,000 at 12%, 6 years):</strong>
    <table>
      <tr><th>Frequency</th><th>m value</th><th>Effective Rate</th><th>Higher FV?</th></tr>
      <tr><td>Annual</td><td>1</td><td>12%</td><td>Lowest</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Semi-annual</td><td>2</td><td>12.36%</td><td>↑</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Quarterly</td><td>4</td><td>12.55%</td><td>↑↑</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Monthly</td><td>12</td><td>12.68%</td><td>↑↑↑</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Continuous</td><td>∞</td><td>12.75%</td><td>Highest</td></tr>
    </table>
    <strong>Rule of 72:</strong> Doubling Period ≈ 72/interest rate<br><br>
    <strong>III. Present Value – Discounting</strong>
    <div class="formula">PV = FV / (1 + k)ⁿ  [Single Cash Flow]
PV = Σ [Aₜ / (1+k)ᵗ]  [Uneven Series of Cash Flows]</div>
    <strong>IV. Annuities</strong><br>
    Regular Annuity: Cash flows at END of period. FV = A × FVIFA(k,n)<br>
    Annuity Due: Cash flows at BEGINNING of period. FV = A × FVIFA(k,n) × (1+k)<br><br>
    <strong>V. Changing Interest Rates</strong><br>
    When interest rates vary each year:
    <div class="formula">FV = PV × (1+k₁)(1+k₂)(1+k₃)...
Average rate = (k₁+k₂+k₃.../n) is WRONG — must use geometric average</div>
    <strong>VI. Applications in Financial Decisions:</strong>
    <ul class="list">
      <li><em>Capital Budgeting:</em> NPV method uses discounting to evaluate projects</li>
      <li><em>Bond Valuation:</em> Present value of future coupon payments + face value</li>
      <li><em>Loan Amortisation:</em> EMI calculation using annuity formula</li>
      <li><em>Retirement Planning:</em> FV of regular savings</li>
      <li><em>Lease vs. Buy decisions:</em> Comparing PV of lease payments vs. purchase price</li>
    </ul>
  </div>
</div>

