<div id="unit10" class="unit-header" style="border-left-color: var(--accent4);">
  <div class="unit-num" style="color:var(--accent4)">Unit 10</div>
  <h2>Cost of Capital</h2>
</div>

<div class="warn-box"><strong>Key Formula Memory:</strong> Kd (debentures), Kt (term loans), Kp (preference), Ke (equity), Kr (retained earnings), WACC (weighted average)</div>

<div class="section-band"><span class="mark-pill m5">5 Marks</span><hr></div>

<div class="qa-card">
  <div class="qa-q"><div class="qnum">1</div>What is Cost of Capital? Why is it important?</div>
  <div class="qa-a">
    <span class="key-term">Cost of Capital</span> is the <em>minimum rate of return</em> a firm must earn on its investments to satisfy its investors. It is the rate of discount which equates the present value of expected payments to a source of finance with the net proceeds received from that source.<br><br>
    <strong>Importance:</strong>
    <ul class="list">
      <li>Used as a <em>hurdle rate</em> in capital budgeting – projects must earn at least the cost of capital</li>
      <li>Helps design optimal capital structure (debt-equity mix)</li>
      <li>Basis for evaluating financial performance</li>
      <li>Key in dividend policy decisions</li>
      <li>Helps minimise shareholder wealth erosion</li>
    </ul>
  </div>
</div>

<div class="qa-card">
  <div class="qa-q"><div class="qnum">2</div>What is Cost of Debentures (Kd)? Give the formula and example.</div>
  <div class="qa-a">
    Cost of debenture = post-tax cost since interest on debentures is tax-deductible.<br><br>
    <div class="formula">Kd = [I(1−t) + (F−P)/n] / [(F+P)/2]<br>
Where: I = Annual interest | t = Tax rate | F = Redemption price | P = Net proceeds | n = Maturity</div>
    <strong>Example (ABC Ltd.):</strong> 15% Debenture, FV ₹100, Redeemable at ₹105 after 7 yrs, Net proceeds ₹95, Tax 50%<br>
    I = ₹15, I(1−t) = 15×0.5 = ₹7.5<br>
    Kd = [7.5 + (105−95)/7] / [(105+95)/2] = [7.5 + 1.43] / 100 = 8.93/100 ≈ <strong>8.93%</strong>
  </div>
</div>

<div class="qa-card">
  <div class="qa-q"><div class="qnum">3</div>What is Cost of Preference Capital (Kp)?</div>
  <div class="qa-a">
    Cost of preference capital is the discount rate which equates proceeds from preference shares to dividend payments and principal repayments.<br>
    <strong>Note:</strong> Preference dividends are <em>NOT</em> tax deductible (unlike debenture interest).<br><br>
    <div class="formula">Kp = [D + (F−P)/n] / [(F+P)/2]<br>
Where: D = Preference dividend | F = Redemption price | P = Net proceeds | n = Maturity</div>
    <strong>Example (XYZ Ltd.):</strong> 15% Preference Shares, FV ₹100, redeemable at ₹100 after 10 yrs, Net proceeds ₹95<br>
    D = ₹15, F = ₹100, P = ₹95, n = 10<br>
    Kp = [15 + (100−95)/10] / [(100+95)/2] = [15 + 0.5] / 97.5 = 15.5/97.5 ≈ <strong>15.9%</strong>
  </div>
</div>

<div class="qa-card">
  <div class="qa-q"><div class="qnum">4</div>Explain the approaches to calculate Cost of Equity Capital (Ke).</div>
  <div class="qa-a">
    <strong>Four Approaches:</strong><br><br>
    <strong>1. Dividend Forecast Approach (Gordon's Model):</strong>
    <div class="formula">Ke = D₁/P₀ + g<br>D₁ = Expected dividend at end of year 1 | P₀ = Current market price | g = Constant growth rate</div>
    Example: D₁=₹14, P₀=₹136, g=9% → Ke = 14/136 + 0.09 = 10.3% + 9% = <strong>19.3%</strong><br><br>
    <strong>2. CAPM Approach:</strong>
    <div class="formula">ki = Rf + βi(Rm − Rf)<br>Rf = Risk-free rate | β = Beta of security | Rm = Market portfolio return</div>
    Example: Rf=10%, β=1.5, Rm=12.5% → ki = 10 + 1.5(12.5−10) = 10 + 3.75 = <strong>13.75%</strong><br><br>
    <strong>3. Earnings-Price (E/P) Ratio Approach:</strong>
    <div class="formula">Ke = E₁ / P₀<br>E₁ = Expected EPS next year | P₀ = Current market price</div>
    <strong>4. Bond Yield + Risk Premium Approach:</strong>
    <div class="formula">Ke = Yield on long-term bonds + Risk premium</div>
  </div>
</div>

<div class="qa-card">
  <div class="qa-q"><div class="qnum">5</div>What is WACC (Weighted Average Cost of Capital)?</div>
  <div class="qa-a">
    <span class="key-term">WACC</span> is the average cost of all sources of capital, weighted by their proportion in the total capital structure.<br><br>
    <div class="formula">WACC = Σ (Wᵢ × Kᵢ)<br>Wᵢ = Weight (proportion) of each source | Kᵢ = Cost of each source</div>
    <strong>Example:</strong>
    <table>
      <tr><th>Source</th><th>Amount</th><th>Weight (W)</th><th>Cost (K)</th><th>W × K</th></tr>
      <tr><td>Equity</td><td>₹4,00,000</td><td>0.40</td><td>15%</td><td>6.00%</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Preference</td><td>₹2,00,000</td><td>0.20</td><td>12%</td><td>2.40%</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Debentures</td><td>₹4,00,000</td><td>0.40</td><td>8%</td><td>3.20%</td></tr>
      <tr><td colspan="4"><strong>WACC</strong></td><td><strong>11.60%</strong></td></tr>
    </table>
    <div class="tip-box">WACC is the <em>discount rate</em> used in NPV calculations and capital budgeting decisions. A project must earn more than WACC to add value.</div>
  </div>
</div>

<div class="section-band"><span class="mark-pill m20">20 Marks</span><hr></div>

<div class="qa-card">
  <div class="qa-q"><div class="qnum">1</div>Explain all components of Cost of Capital with formulas, examples, and the concept of WACC and Opportunity Cost of Capital.</div>
  <div class="qa-a">
    <strong>I. Cost of Term Loans (Kt):</strong>
    <div class="formula">Kt = I × (1 − t)<br>I = Interest rate | t = Corporate tax rate</div>
    Since interest on term loans is tax-deductible, the effective cost is after-tax.<br><br>
    <strong>II. Cost of Retained Earnings (Kr):</strong>
    <div class="formula">Kr = Ke  (Cost of retained earnings = Cost of equity)</div>
    Retained earnings belong to shareholders. The company must earn at least what shareholders expect. <em>No floatation cost</em> → Kr is slightly lower than cost of new equity.<br><br>
    <strong>III. Cost of External Equity (Ke-new):</strong>
    <div class="formula">Ke-new = D₁ / [P₀(1−f)] + g<br>f = Floatation cost as % of current market price</div>
    Floatation costs make external equity more expensive than retained earnings.<br><br>
    <strong>IV. Opportunity Cost of Capital:</strong><br>
    The opportunity cost of capital is the return that could have been earned on the best alternative investment of similar risk. If a firm invests in a project earning 12% but could have earned 15% elsewhere at the same risk → opportunity cost = 15%.<br><br>
    <strong>V. WACC – Weighted Average Cost of Capital:</strong>
    <table>
      <tr><th>Source</th><th>Amount (₹)</th><th>Weight</th><th>After-tax Cost</th><th>Weighted Cost</th></tr>
      <tr><td>Equity (Ke)</td><td>5,00,000</td><td>0.50</td><td>16%</td><td>8.00%</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Preference (Kp)</td><td>1,00,000</td><td>0.10</td><td>14%</td><td>1.40%</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Debentures (Kd)</td><td>3,00,000</td><td>0.30</td><td>7%</td><td>2.10%</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Term Loans (Kt)</td><td>1,00,000</td><td>0.10</td><td>6%</td><td>0.60%</td></tr>
      <tr><td colspan="4"><strong>WACC</strong></td><td><strong>12.10%</strong></td></tr>
    </table>
    <strong>VI. Significance of Cost of Capital:</strong>
    <ul class="list">
      <li>Capital budgeting decisions: Accept projects with IRR > WACC</li>
      <li>Capital structure design: Find optimal debt-equity ratio</li>
      <li>Performance evaluation: Economic Value Added (EVA) = NOPAT − (WACC × Capital)</li>
      <li>Dividend decisions: Retain earnings only if ROE > WACC</li>
    </ul>
  </div>
</div>

<!-- ══════════════════════════════════ UNIT 11 ══════════════════════════════════ -->
<div id="unit11" class="unit-header" style="border-left-color: var(--purple);">
  <div class="unit-num" style="color:var(--purple)">Unit 11</div>
  <h2>Investment Appraisal Methods (Capital Budgeting)</h2>
</div>

<div class="warn-box"><strong>Methods to Remember:</strong> Non-Discounted → Payback Period, ARR | Discounted → NPV, IRR, PI</div>

<div class="section-band"><span class="mark-pill m5">5 Marks</span><hr></div>

<div class="qa-card">
  <div class="qa-q"><div class="qnum">1</div>What is Capital Budgeting? State its importance.</div>
  <div class="qa-a">
    <span class="key-term">Capital Budgeting</span> (Investment Appraisal) is a financial management tool to measure a project's potential risks and expected long-term return on investment. It evaluates and ranks the value of projects requiring large capital investment.<br><br>
    <strong>Importance:</strong>
    <ul class="list">
      <li>Large amounts of money involved → irreversible decisions</li>
      <li>Long-term impact on firm's profitability and growth</li>
      <li>Helps compare and select from competing projects</li>
      <li>Measures value of a project throughout its life cycle</li>
      <li>Considers risk and uncertainty of future cash flows</li>
    </ul>
    <strong>Two Types of Risk in Capital Budgeting:</strong>
    <ul class="list">
      <li><em>Sales Risk:</em> Uncertainty about units sold and price realised</li>
      <li><em>Operating Risk:</em> Uncertainty from mix of fixed and variable costs</li>
    </ul>
  </div>
</div>

<div class="qa-card">
  <div class="qa-q"><div class="qnum">2</div>Explain the Payback Period Method with merits and demerits.</div>
  <div class="qa-a">
    <span class="key-term">Payback Period</span> = Number of years required to recover the initial investment from cash inflows.<br><br>
    <div class="formula">Payback Period = Initial Investment / Annual Cash Inflow  [if uniform cash flows]</div>
    For uneven cash flows → cumulate cash inflows year by year till they equal investment.<br><br>
    <strong>Example:</strong> Project X costs ₹1,00,000. Cash inflows: Yr1=₹20,000, Yr2=₹20,000, Yr3=₹30,000, Yr4=₹30,000 → Payback = 4 years. Project Y costs ₹1,00,000. Yr1=₹25,000, Yr2=₹25,000, Yr3=₹50,000 → Payback = 3 years. <strong>Select Y</strong> (shorter payback).<br><br>
    <table>
      <tr><th>Merits</th><th>Demerits</th></tr>
      <tr><td>Simple and easy to understand</td><td>Ignores time value of money</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Useful for capital rationing</td><td>Ignores cash flows beyond payback period</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Identifies liquidity quickly</td><td>Does not indicate accept/reject decision</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Good for high-uncertainty environments</td><td>Biased against long-term projects</td></tr>
    </table>
  </div>
</div>

<div class="qa-card">
  <div class="qa-q"><div class="qnum">3</div>Explain the Accounting Rate of Return (ARR) method.</div>
  <div class="qa-a">
    <span class="key-term">ARR</span> = Ratio of average annual profit after tax to average investment. Uses accounting data (not cash flows).<br><br>
    <div class="formula">ARR = (Average Annual Net Profit after Tax / Average Investment) × 100
Average Investment = (Initial Investment + Salvage Value) / 2</div>
    <strong>Example:</strong> Capital expenditure ₹5,00,000. Profits: ₹40,000+₹80,000+₹90,000+₹30,000 = Total ₹2,40,000<br>
    Average annual profit = 2,40,000/4 = ₹60,000<br>
    Average investment = 5,00,000/2 = ₹2,50,000<br>
    ARR = (60,000/2,50,000) × 100 = <strong>24%</strong><br><br>
    <table>
      <tr><th>Merits</th><th>Demerits</th></tr>
      <tr><td>Easy to calculate</td><td>Ignores time value of money</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Uses readily available accounting data</td><td>Depreciation policy affects results</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Considers all years of project life</td><td>Subjective acceptance criteria</td></tr>
    </table>
  </div>
</div>

<div class="qa-card">
  <div class="qa-q"><div class="qnum">4</div>Explain the Net Present Value (NPV) Method with merits and demerits.</div>
  <div class="qa-a">
    <span class="key-term">NPV</span> = Present value of all future cash inflows − Initial investment. Uses discounting at the firm's cost of capital.<br><br>
    <div class="formula">NPV = Σ [Cₜ / (1+k)ᵗ] − C₀<br>C₀ = Initial investment | Cₜ = Cash flow at time t | k = Discount rate</div>
    <strong>Decision Rule:</strong> If NPV &gt; 0 → <strong>Accept</strong> | If NPV &lt; 0 → <strong>Reject</strong><br><br>
    <strong>Example:</strong> Invest ₹10,000. Inflows: Y1=₹4,000, Y2=₹5,000, Y3=₹4,000. Discount rate=10%
    <table>
      <tr><th>Year</th><th>Cash Flow</th><th>Discount Factor @10%</th><th>Present Value</th></tr>
      <tr><td>0</td><td>₹10,000</td><td>1.000</td><td>₹10,000 (outflow)</td></tr>
      <tr><td>1</td><td>₹4,000</td><td>0.909</td><td>₹3,636</td></tr>
      <tr><td>2</td><td>₹5,000</td><td>0.826</td><td>₹4,130</td></tr>
      <tr><td>3</td><td>₹4,000</td><td>0.751</td><td>₹3,004</td></tr>
      <tr><td colspan="3"><strong>NPV = 3,636+4,130+3,004−10,000</strong></td><td><strong>+₹770 (Accept)</strong></td></tr>
    </table>
    <table>
      <tr><th>Merits</th><th>Demerits</th></tr>
      <tr><td>Recognizes time value of money</td><td>Difficult to calculate</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Considers all cash flows over project life</td><td>Finding discount rate is complex</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Best for mutually exclusive projects</td><td>Absolute measure – favours larger projects</td></tr>
    </table>
  </div>
</div>

<div class="qa-card">
  <div class="qa-q"><div class="qnum">5</div>Explain the Internal Rate of Return (IRR) Method.</div>
  <div class="qa-a">
    <span class="key-term">IRR</span> = The discount rate at which NPV = 0. It is the rate that equates PV of future cash flows to the initial investment.<br><br>
    <div class="formula">IRR → Solve: Σ [Cₜ / (1+r)ᵗ] = C₀  [where r = IRR]</div>
    <strong>Decision Rule:</strong> If IRR &gt; Cost of Capital → <strong>Accept</strong> | If IRR &lt; Cost of Capital → <strong>Reject</strong><br><br>
    <strong>How to calculate IRR:</strong> Trial and error method:<br>
    1. Calculate a Factor: F = Initial Investment / Average Annual Cash Inflow<br>
    2. Look up this factor in the PVIFA table at the project's life span<br>
    3. Interpolate between two discount rates<br><br>
    <div class="formula">IRR = Lower Rate + [(NPV at Lower Rate) / (NPV at Lower Rate − NPV at Higher Rate)] × (Higher Rate − Lower Rate)</div>
    <table>
      <tr><th>Merits</th><th>Demerits</th></tr>
      <tr><td>Considers time value of money</td><td>Difficult trial-and-error calculation</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Expressed as percentage (easy to compare)</td><td>May give multiple IRRs for unconventional cash flows</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Considers all cash flows</td><td>May conflict with NPV in ranking mutually exclusive projects</td></tr>
    </table>
    <div class="tip-box"><strong>NPV vs IRR:</strong> NPV gives absolute value; IRR gives percentage. For mutually exclusive projects, <em>prefer NPV</em> as IRR can be misleading when project sizes differ.</div>
  </div>
</div>

<div class="section-band"><span class="mark-pill m20">20 Marks</span><hr></div>

