<div class="qa-card">
  <div class="qa-q"><div class="qnum">3</div>List and explain the factors influencing Working Capital requirements.</div>
  <div class="qa-a">
    <table>
      <tr><th>Factor</th><th>Effect on WC</th></tr>
      <tr><td><strong>Nature of Business</strong></td><td>Manufacturing needs more WC (stock+debtors); utilities/services need less</td></tr>
      <tr><td><strong>Business Cycle</strong></td><td>Boom → higher production → higher WC; Recession → stock piles up → higher WC</td></tr>
      <tr><td><strong>Seasonal Variations</strong></td><td>Seasonal demand → higher WC during peak season</td></tr>
      <tr><td><strong>Size of Business</strong></td><td>Larger firms → more WC for current assets and liabilities</td></tr>
      <tr><td><strong>Technology</strong></td><td>Better technology → less inventory → less WC required</td></tr>
      <tr><td><strong>Operating Cycle Length</strong></td><td>Longer cycle → more WC needed</td></tr>
      <tr><td><strong>Credit Policy</strong></td><td>Liberal credit → more debtors → more WC blocked</td></tr>
    </table>
  </div>
</div>

<div class="qa-card">
  <div class="qa-q"><div class="qnum">4</div>What are the Sources of Working Capital Finance?</div>
  <div class="qa-a">
    <table>
      <tr><th>Category</th><th>Sources</th></tr>
      <tr><td><strong>Spontaneous Sources</strong></td><td>Trade creditors, Bills/Notes payable, Accrued expenses, Deferred tax</td></tr>
      <tr><td><strong>Short-term Negotiated</strong></td><td>Bank overdraft/Cash credit, Trade deposits, Public deposits, Bills discounting, Commercial paper, Short-term loans</td></tr>
      <tr><td><strong>Long-term Internal</strong></td><td>Retained profits, Provision for depreciation</td></tr>
      <tr><td><strong>Long-term External</strong></td><td>Share capital, Long-term loans, Debentures</td></tr>
    </table>
    <div class="tip-box"><strong>Trade Credit</strong> is the most popular spontaneous source (contributes ~1/3 of short-term credit). Types: Open Account (no formal instrument) → shown as Sundry Creditors; With formal instrument → shown as Bills Payable.</div>
    <strong>Invoice Discounting / Factoring:</strong> A factoring company pays the selling company for its debtors (less a percentage) and then collects from debtors when due. Helps the seller get funds 1-2 months earlier.
  </div>
</div>

<div class="section-band"><span class="mark-pill m20">20 Marks</span><hr></div>

<div class="qa-card">
  <div class="qa-q"><div class="qnum">1</div>Explain Working Capital Management in detail – concept, operating cycle, factors, sources, and strategies.</div>
  <div class="qa-a">
    <strong>I. Working Capital Management – Objective:</strong><br>
    Maintain adequate liquidity to run day-to-day operations while minimising cost of financing current assets.<br><br>
    <strong>II. Characteristics of Current Assets:</strong>
    <ul class="list">
      <li>Short life span (7-90 days typically)</li>
      <li>Swift transformation into other asset forms (RM → WIP → FG → Debtors → Cash)</li>
    </ul>
    <strong>III. Nature of Working Capital Management vs Long-term Financial Management:</strong>
    <table>
      <tr><th>Point</th><th>Working Capital (Short-term)</th><th>Long-term Finance</th></tr>
      <tr><td>Amount</td><td>Relatively small, frequent</td><td>Large, one-time</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Time Impact</td><td>Within operating cycle (3 months–1 year)</td><td>15-20+ years</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Focus</td><td>Liquidity + Operating cycle</td><td>Profitability + Growth</td></tr>
    </table>
    <strong>IV. Three Strategies of Working Capital Management:</strong>
    <table>
      <tr><th>Strategy</th><th>Approach</th><th>Risk-Return</th></tr>
      <tr><td><strong>Conservative</strong></td><td>Higher CA, use more long-term funds</td><td>Low risk, Low return</td></tr>
      <tr><td><strong>Aggressive</strong></td><td>Lower CA, use more short-term funds</td><td>High risk, High return</td></tr>
      <tr><td><strong>Moderate/Matching</strong></td><td>Match maturity of funds with need (short-term assets → short-term funds)</td><td>Balanced</td></tr>
    </table>
    <strong>V. Estimating Working Capital Requirement:</strong><br>
    Working capital requirement is estimated by calculating each component:
    <ul class="list">
      <li>Raw Material Inventory = (Annual RM consumption / 12) × Months of holding</li>
      <li>WIP Inventory = (Cost of Production / 12) × Months of processing</li>
      <li>Finished Goods Inventory = (Cost of Goods Sold / 12) × Months of holding</li>
      <li>Debtors = (Annual Credit Sales / 12) × Debtor collection months</li>
      <li>Less: Creditors = (Annual Credit Purchases / 12) × Credit period from suppliers</li>
      <li>Add: Safety margin (usually 10-15% of net WC)</li>
    </ul>
  </div>
</div>

