<div id="unit13" class="unit-header" style="border-left-color: var(--accent2);">
  <div class="unit-num" style="color:var(--accent2)">Unit 13</div>
  <h2>Cash and Treasury Management</h2>
</div>

<div class="section-band"><span class="mark-pill m5">5 Marks</span><hr></div>

<div class="qa-card">
  <div class="qa-q"><div class="qnum">1</div>What are the motives for holding cash? (Keynes' 3 Motives)</div>
  <div class="qa-a">
    <span class="key-term">Three Motives for Holding Cash</span> (by John Maynard Keynes):<br><br>
    <table>
      <tr><th>Motive</th><th>Reason</th><th>Example</th></tr>
      <tr><td><strong>Transaction Motive</strong></td><td>To meet routine day-to-day payments</td><td>Paying wages, rent, utilities, suppliers</td></tr>
      <tr><td><strong>Precautionary Motive</strong></td><td>To meet unexpected or emergency payments</td><td>Sudden repair of machinery, emergency purchase</td></tr>
      <tr><td><strong>Speculative Motive</strong></td><td>To take advantage of unexpected profitable opportunities</td><td>Buying materials when prices fall suddenly</td></tr>
    </table>
    <div class="tip-box">Firms primarily hold cash for Transaction and Precautionary motives. Speculative motive is secondary and depends on market conditions.</div>
  </div>
</div>

<div class="qa-card">
  <div class="qa-q"><div class="qnum">2</div>What is Cash Planning / Cash Budget? Why is it prepared?</div>
  <div class="qa-a">
    <span class="key-term">Cash Budget</span> is a statement showing <em>estimated cash receipts and payments</em> for a future period (monthly/quarterly). It helps management plan for cash shortfalls and arrange overdraft facilities in advance.<br><br>
    <strong>Purpose of Cash Budget:</strong>
    <ul class="list">
      <li>Anticipate cash shortfalls → arrange borrowings in advance</li>
      <li>Identify surplus cash → plan investments to earn returns</li>
      <li>Plan timing of major purchases and payments</li>
      <li>Improve cash flow management efficiency</li>
      <li>Required by banks for granting overdraft/CC facilities</li>
    </ul>
    <strong>Format of Cash Budget:</strong>
    <table>
      <tr><th>Particulars</th><th>Month 1 (₹)</th><th>Month 2 (₹)</th><th>Month 3 (₹)</th></tr>
      <tr><td>A. Opening Cash Balance</td><td>XX</td><td>XX</td><td>XX</td></tr>
      <tr><td>B. Receipts: Cash Sales, Debtors collected, Other income</td><td>XX</td><td>XX</td><td>XX</td></tr>
      <tr><td>C. Total Available (A+B)</td><td>XX</td><td>XX</td><td>XX</td></tr>
      <tr><td>D. Payments: Purchases, Wages, Overheads, Capital Expenditure</td><td>XX</td><td>XX</td><td>XX</td></tr>
      <tr><td>E. Closing Balance (C−D)</td><td>XX</td><td>XX</td><td>XX</td></tr>
      <tr><td>F. Surplus/(Deficit) = Overdraft Required</td><td>XX</td><td>XX</td><td>XX</td></tr>
    </table>
  </div>
</div>

<div class="qa-card">
  <div class="qa-q"><div class="qnum">3</div>What is the Optimum Cash Balance? Explain the Baumol Model.</div>
  <div class="qa-a">
    <span class="key-term">Optimum Cash Balance</span> = The level of cash that minimises the total cost of holding cash (opportunity cost of holding + transaction costs of converting securities to cash).<br><br>
    <strong>Baumol Model</strong> (similar to EOQ model for inventory):<br>
    Assumes constant, predictable cash outflows. Cash is raised by selling marketable securities.<br><br>
    <div class="formula">Optimal Cash = √(2 × T × C) / I<br>
T = Total cash needed per period | C = Fixed cost per transaction | I = Opportunity cost (interest rate)</div>
    <strong>Trade-off:</strong>
    <ul class="list">
      <li>High cash balance → high opportunity cost (idle money not earning returns)</li>
      <li>Low cash balance → frequent conversions → high transaction costs</li>
    </ul>
    Optimum is where <em>opportunity cost = transaction cost</em> (total cost minimised).
  </div>
</div>

<div class="qa-card">
  <div class="qa-q"><div class="qnum">4</div>How is surplus cash invested? What instruments are used?</div>
  <div class="qa-a">
    When a firm has surplus cash beyond its optimum balance, it invests in <strong>short-term marketable securities</strong> to earn returns:<br><br>
    <table>
      <tr><th>Instrument</th><th>Features</th></tr>
      <tr><td>Treasury Bills (T-Bills)</td><td>Government issued, very safe, highly liquid, short-term (91/182/364 days)</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Commercial Paper (CP)</td><td>Unsecured promissory note by corporates, short-term (15 days to 1 year)</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Certificate of Deposit (CD)</td><td>Issued by banks, fixed interest, short-term</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Money Market Mutual Funds</td><td>Pooled investment in short-term instruments</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Inter-corporate Deposits</td><td>Short-term loans between companies</td></tr>
    </table>
    <strong>Selection Criteria:</strong> Safety (risk) → Liquidity (quick convertibility) → Return (yield)
  </div>
</div>

<div class="qa-card">
  <div class="qa-q"><div class="qnum">5</div>What is Float? Explain the types of float in cash management.</div>
  <div class="qa-a">
    <span class="key-term">Float</span> = The difference between the bank balance shown in the firm's books and the actual balance in the bank. It represents funds in transit.<br><br>
    <table>
      <tr><th>Type of Float</th><th>Meaning</th><th>Effect on Firm</th></tr>
      <tr><td><strong>Payment Float (Disbursement Float)</strong></td><td>Cheques issued but not yet cleared from bank</td><td>Favourable – firm's book balance is less than bank balance</td></tr>
      <tr><td><strong>Collection Float</strong></td><td>Cheques received but not yet cleared into account</td><td>Unfavourable – firm's book balance is more than bank balance</td></tr>
      <tr><td><strong>Net Float</strong></td><td>Payment Float − Collection Float</td><td>Positive net float = benefit to firm</td></tr>
    </table>
    <strong>Strategies to Manage Float:</strong>
    <ul class="list">
      <li><em>Speed up collections:</em> Lockbox system, concentration banking, electronic transfers</li>
      <li><em>Slow down disbursements:</em> Centralised payment, cheques drawn on distant banks (ethical limits)</li>
    </ul>
  </div>
</div>

<div class="section-band"><span class="mark-pill m20">20 Marks</span><hr></div>

<div class="qa-card">
  <div class="qa-q"><div class="qnum">1</div>Explain Cash Management in detail – motives, planning, cash budget preparation, optimum cash balance, and treasury management.</div>
  <div class="qa-a">
    <strong>I. Facets of Cash Management:</strong>
    <ul class="list">
      <li><em>Cash Planning:</em> Prepare cash budget – forecast inflows and outflows</li>
      <li><em>Managing Cash Flows:</em> Accelerate collections, control disbursements, manage float</li>
      <li><em>Optimum Cash Level:</em> Neither too much (opportunity cost) nor too little (insolvency risk)</li>
      <li><em>Investing Surplus Cash:</em> Short-term marketable securities to earn returns</li>
    </ul>
    <strong>II. Comprehensive Cash Budget Illustration:</strong><br>
    ABC Co. – Overdraft needed April to June (manufacturing for stock)<br>
    Key assumptions: 50% credit sales collected next month, 50% two months later. Creditors paid next month.
    <table>
      <tr><th>Particulars</th><th>April (₹)</th><th>May (₹)</th><th>June (₹)</th></tr>
      <tr><td>Receipts: 50% of Feb sales (₹1,80,000)</td><td>90,000</td><td>—</td><td>—</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Receipts: 50% of March sales (₹1,92,000)</td><td>96,000</td><td>96,000</td><td>—</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Receipts: 50% of April sales (₹1,08,000)</td><td>—</td><td>54,000</td><td>54,000</td></tr>
      <tr><td><strong>Total Receipts</strong></td><td><strong>1,86,000</strong></td><td><strong>1,50,000</strong></td><td><strong>54,000</strong></td></tr>
      <tr><td>Payments: Purchases (prev month)</td><td>1,44,000</td><td>2,43,000</td><td>2,46,000</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Payments: Wages</td><td>11,000</td><td>10,000</td><td>15,000</td></tr>
      <tr><td><strong>Total Payments</strong></td><td><strong>1,55,000</strong></td><td><strong>2,53,000</strong></td><td><strong>2,61,000</strong></td></tr>
      <tr><td><strong>Net Surplus/(Deficit)</strong></td><td><strong>+31,000</strong></td><td><strong>−1,03,000</strong></td><td><strong>−2,07,000</strong></td></tr>
    </table>
    <strong>III. Treasury Management:</strong><br>
    Treasury Management = Managing the firm's cash, investments, debt, and financial risks.<br>
    Key functions:
    <ul class="list">
      <li>Short-term investment of surplus funds</li>
      <li>Banking relationship management</li>
      <li>Foreign exchange risk management</li>
      <li>Interest rate risk management</li>
      <li>Debt management and refinancing</li>
    </ul>
  </div>
