<!-- ══════════════════════════════════ UNIT 15 ══════════════════════════════════ -->
<div id="unit15" class="unit-header" style="border-left-color: var(--accent4);">
  <div class="unit-num" style="color:var(--accent4)">Unit 15</div>
  <h2>Inventory Management</h2>
</div>

<div class="section-band"><span class="mark-pill m5">5 Marks</span><hr></div>

<div class="qa-card">
  <div class="qa-q"><div class="qnum">1</div>What is Inventory Management? Why do firms hold inventory?</div>
  <div class="qa-a">
    <span class="key-term">Inventory Management</span> helps companies identify which and how much stock to order and at what time. It tracks inventory from purchase to sale.<br><br>
    <strong>Types of Inventory in a Manufacturing Firm:</strong>
    <ul class="list">
      <li>Raw Material – to ensure production is not disrupted</li>
      <li>Work-in-Process (WIP) – goods being processed</li>
      <li>Finished Goods – ready for sale</li>
      <li>Spares/Maintenance items – for machinery upkeep</li>
    </ul>
    <strong>Reasons for Holding Inventory:</strong>
    <ul class="list">
      <li>Ensure uninterrupted production (buffer against supply delays)</li>
      <li>Meet customer demand without stockouts (lost sales)</li>
      <li>Seasonal demand patterns require advance stocking</li>
      <li>Take advantage of bulk purchase discounts</li>
      <li>Hedge against future price increases</li>
    </ul>
    <div class="warn-box">Inventory typically represents 15-30% of total assets in manufacturing firms. Over-inventory = blocked funds; Under-inventory = production disruption.</div>
  </div>
</div>

<div class="qa-card">
  <div class="qa-q"><div class="qnum">2</div>What is EOQ (Economic Order Quantity)? Give the formula and example.</div>
  <div class="qa-a">
    <span class="key-term">EOQ</span> = The order quantity that minimises the total of ordering costs and carrying (holding) costs.<br><br>
    <div class="formula">Total Cost (TC) = (U/Q) × F + (Q/2) × P × C

EOQ = √(2FU / PC)

Where:
U = Annual demand (units)
Q = Order size (units)
F = Fixed cost per order (ordering cost)
P = Purchase price per unit
C = Annual carrying cost as % of average inventory value</div>
    <strong>Key Insight:</strong>
    <ul class="list">
      <li>Ordering cost = (U/Q) × F → DECREASES as order size Q increases</li>
      <li>Carrying cost = (Q/2) × P × C → INCREASES as order size Q increases</li>
      <li>EOQ = Point where both costs are EQUAL → Total cost is MINIMUM</li>
    </ul>
    <strong>Example (Ace Company):</strong><br>
    U = 20,000 units, F = ₹500 per order, P = ₹5 per unit, C = 20% per year
    <div class="formula">EOQ = √(2 × 500 × 20,000) / (5 × 0.20) = √(2,00,00,000/1) = √2,00,00,000 ≈ 2,000 units</div>
  </div>
</div>

<div class="qa-card">
  <div class="qa-q"><div class="qnum">3</div>Explain ABC Analysis in inventory management.</div>
  <div class="qa-a">
    <span class="key-term">ABC Analysis</span> classifies inventory items based on their <strong>value and importance</strong>, so management attention is focused where it matters most.<br><br>
    <table>
      <tr><th>Category</th><th>Description</th><th>% of Items</th><th>% of Value</th><th>Control</th></tr>
      <tr><td><strong>A – High Value</strong></td><td>Few items, very high value</td><td>~10-15%</td><td>~70-75%</td><td>Tight control, frequent review, low safety stock</td></tr>
      <tr><td><strong>B – Medium Value</strong></td><td>Moderate items, moderate value</td><td>~20-25%</td><td>~20-25%</td><td>Moderate control, periodic review</td></tr>
      <tr><td><strong>C – Low Value</strong></td><td>Many items, low value</td><td>~60-70%</td><td>~5-10%</td><td>Simple control, high safety stock, bulk orders</td></tr>
    </table>
    <div class="tip-box"><strong>Memory Trick:</strong> A = Always control closely | B = Better to review periodically | C = Casual review is fine</div>
  </div>
</div>

<div class="qa-card">
  <div class="qa-q"><div class="qnum">4</div>Explain the Reorder Point and Safety Stock concepts.</div>
  <div class="qa-a">
    <span class="key-term">Reorder Point (ROP)</span> = The inventory level at which a new order should be placed so that stock doesn't run out before the new order arrives.<br><br>
    <div class="formula">Reorder Point = Lead Time Demand + Safety Stock
Lead Time Demand = Daily Usage × Lead Time (days)
Safety Stock = (Maximum Usage − Normal Usage) × Lead Time</div>
    <span class="key-term">Safety Stock (Buffer Stock)</span> = Extra inventory held to protect against unexpected demand increase or supply delays.<br><br>
    <strong>Example:</strong> Daily usage = 100 units, Lead time = 5 days, Safety stock = 200 units<br>
    ROP = (100 × 5) + 200 = 500 + 200 = <strong>700 units</strong><br>
    → When inventory falls to 700 units, place a new order.
  </div>
</div>

<div class="qa-card">
  <div class="qa-q"><div class="qnum">5</div>What are the objectives of Inventory Management?</div>
  <div class="qa-a">
    <ul class="list">
      <li>Ensure <em>uninterrupted production</em> and smooth operations</li>
      <li>Minimise <em>investment in inventory</em> (reduce blocked capital)</li>
      <li>Avoid <em>stockouts</em> that lead to lost sales and customer dissatisfaction</li>
      <li>Prevent <em>obsolescence</em> (especially for perishables and fast-changing goods)</li>
      <li>Minimise <em>total inventory costs</em> (ordering + carrying + stockout costs)</li>
      <li>Maintain <em>optimum stock levels</em> – neither too much nor too little</li>
      <li>Support production/marketing coordination</li>
    </ul>
  </div>
</div>

<div class="section-band"><span class="mark-pill m20">20 Marks</span><hr></div>

<div class="qa-card">
  <div class="qa-q"><div class="qnum">1</div>Explain all Techniques of Inventory Control – Traditional and Modern – in detail with EOQ, ABC Analysis, JIT, and VED Analysis.</div>
  <div class="qa-a">
    <strong>I. Traditional Techniques of Inventory Control:</strong><br><br>
    <strong>1. Economic Order Quantity (EOQ):</strong><br>
    Minimises total ordering + carrying cost.<br>
    <div class="formula">EOQ = √(2FU/PC)   |   TC = (U/Q)×F + (Q/2)×P×C</div>
    Assumptions of EOQ model:
    <ul class="list">
      <li>Constant and known annual demand</li>
      <li>Constant purchase price (no quantity discounts)</li>
      <li>Fixed ordering cost per order</li>
      <li>Constant carrying cost per unit</li>
      <li>Instantaneous delivery (no lead time)</li>
    </ul>
    <strong>2. ABC Analysis:</strong> Classify inventory by value importance (A=high, B=medium, C=low). Focus control on A items.<br><br>
    <strong>3. Reorder Point + Safety Stock:</strong> Trigger point for placing orders. Safety stock guards against supply/demand uncertainty.<br><br>
    <strong>4. VED Analysis (Vital, Essential, Desirable):</strong> Classifies items by criticality to production (used for spare parts):
    <table>
      <tr><th>Category</th><th>Description</th><th>Control</th></tr>
      <tr><td>Vital (V)</td><td>Production halts without it</td><td>Always keep high stock</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Essential (E)</td><td>Production slows without it</td><td>Maintain safety stock</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Desirable (D)</td><td>Can manage without it temporarily</td><td>Order as needed</td></tr>
    </table>
    <strong>5. Maximum-Minimum Stock Level:</strong>
    <div class="formula">Maximum Stock Level = ROL + EOQ − (Minimum Usage × Minimum Lead Time)
Minimum Stock Level = ROL − (Average Usage × Average Lead Time)
Average Stock Level = (Maximum + Minimum) / 2</div>
    <strong>II. Modern Techniques of Inventory Control:</strong><br><br>
    <strong>1. Just-In-Time (JIT) System:</strong>
    <ul class="list">
      <li>Inventory ordered and received <em>exactly when needed</em> in production</li>
      <li>Aim: Zero inventory → no holding costs, no obsolescence</li>
      <li>Requires perfect supplier relationships and precise demand forecasting</li>
      <li>Origin: Toyota Production System (Japan)</li>
    </ul>
    <strong>2. Materials Requirements Planning (MRP):</strong>
    <ul class="list">
      <li>Computer-based system that plans raw material orders based on production schedule</li>
      <li>Works backward from finished goods requirement to determine RM order timing</li>
    </ul>
    <strong>3. Perpetual Inventory System:</strong>
    <ul class="list">
      <li>Continuous recording of every inventory transaction</li>
      <li>Real-time inventory tracking → no need for periodic physical count</li>
    </ul>
    <strong>III. Costs of Inventory (3 Types):</strong>
    <table>
      <tr><th>Cost Type</th><th>Components</th></tr>
      <tr><td>Ordering Costs</td><td>Purchase order cost, inspection, delivery handling</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Carrying/Holding Costs</td><td>Storage, insurance, deterioration, opportunity cost of capital</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Stockout Costs</td><td>Lost sales, idle labour/machines, emergency purchasing at premium</td></tr>
    </table>
    <div class="tip-box"><strong>Total Inventory Cost Minimisation:</strong><br>
    Ordering cost and Carrying cost move in OPPOSITE directions as order size changes.<br>
    EOQ is the sweet spot where both are balanced and total cost is minimum.</div>
  </div>
</div>

